1. Project Statement
Within the past decade the interest in Indian culture in western countries has increased exponentially. Among the various aspects of Indian culture, yoga and Indian food have seen the largest growth in interest. With yoga now becoming a multi-billion dollar industry and Indian cuisine seeing the largest growth in market share in the past few years, there is an untapped market catered toward Indian culture. There is a desire for information about all things Indian but there is no centralized place to find it. IndyaVids has a vision to be a portal of knowledge on all aspects of Indian culture by providing video guides and building an online community that can be accessed by all.

Like all start-ups, has a goal to be financially self sufficient and eventually become profitable. IndyaVids will primarily feature video content on: yoga, Indian cooking and Indian dancing.

The IndyaVids team is currently working on an alpha version of their website which is due for release in June. Creative Dynamic will be doing research and analysis for the beta version of the website that is due for release in September. Creative Dynamic will focus on three areas: Gamification Design, Social Community Design and Site Architecture Design.
Gamification Design - Two major goals: doing research and analysis to recommend a Gamifcation engine and coming up with a design for the game.
Social Community Design - Design a method to increase social interaction and integration with social networking sites.
Site Architecture Design - Analyze and make recommendations on the architecture used to design the site and how to scale it for the future.


After the beta version of the website has been released Creative Dynamic will design a 	mobile application for IndyaVids to be accessed on the iPhone, iPad and Android cell phone and tablet systems.

Users
There are four (4) types of users: Lurkers, Viewers, Content Creators, and Premium Content Creators, with the following hierarchy: Premium Content Creator > Content Creator > Viewer > Lurker. The actions that a Content Creator can perform subsumes the Viewer’s actions and the Premium Content Creator subsumes both of them.

Lurker: A lurker is a user that is not registered. The only actions a lurker does is watch videos. A lurker always has the option to register and become a user.

Viewer: A viewer is a registered user that primarily watches Videos. Viewers are able to rate, comment and save videos, make friends and interact with the community. It is estimated that 80% of all registered users will fall into this category.

Content Creator:  Viewers that occasionally create videos to share with others, an account is required to create and upload a video but otherwise they are no different than a Viewer. Content Creators are considered to be novices in their field and are expected to create less than 3 videos per month. An estimated 10% of all users will fall into this category.

Premium Content Creator: Individuals that are experts in their field and may have a pre-existing brand and fan base. They are expected to create more than 3 high quality videos per month. An estimated 10% of all users will fall into this category.

5. Market Analysis

Currently in the market there are many how-to video sites, Learnable, Howcast, Udemy, etc. These sites feature a very broad range of topics, Indyavids will be the first how-to video website focusing on the niche market of Indian culture. There isn’t much direct competition and the potential for success is high.
According to a recent study done in 2008, people spend 5.7 billion dollars a year on yoga classes and products (Yoga Journal). This figure has increased 87 percent since 2004, it is also estimated that about 12-20 million Americans participate yoga in 2005. These numbers keep increasing every year. In our previous study, we noticed that the main demographic for yoga includes women at the ages between 18-54 who are well-educated and in the upper middle class.
Interest in Indian food has been growing steadily in the past decade, with more and more Indian restaurants opening every year. A September 2009 survey of ethnic food by the market research group Mintel found that the fastest growing segment was Indian food, with sales increasing nearly 35 percent from 2006 to 2008 (Patriot Ledger).
The only competitors Indyavids can consider are the other how-to websites. Although they do not have a specific market some of them do cover a very wide variety. For example, eHow also have tips related in Indian culture, however, as Indyavids launch it would make a clear distinction from regular how-to sites.

Sponsored Advertisements: $100 per ad/per week

Social Analytics:
Detailed Social Analytic Reports: $75 for 1 month report

ROI = ($130,000 - $72,000) / ($72,000) = 80.56% in the first year.
